# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christian-vegetarian-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activism may be performed on a day-to-day basis in a wide variety of ways, including through the creation of art (artivism), computer hacking (hacktivism), or simply in how one chooses to spend their money (economic activism).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] For example, the refusal to buy clothes or other merchandise from a company as a protest against the exploitation of workers by that company could be considered an expression of activism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] However, the term commonly refers to a form of collective action, in which numerous individuals coordinate an act of protest together.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Collective action that is purposeful, organized, and sustained over a period of time becomes known as a social movement.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Historically, activists have used literature, including pamphlets, tracts, and books to disseminate or propagate their messages and attempt to persuade their readers of the justice of their cause.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Research has now begun to explore how contemporary activist groups use social media to facilitate civic engagement and collective action combining politics with technology.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Left-wing and right-wing online activists often use different tactics.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Hashtag activism and offline protest are more common on the left.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Working strategically with partisan media, migrating to alternative platforms, and manipulation of mainstream media are more common on the right (in the United States).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] In addition, the perception of increased left-wing activism in science and academia may decrease conservative trust in science and motivate some forms of conservative activism, including on college campuses.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Some scholars have also shown how the influence of very wealthy Americans is a form of activism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Separating activism and terrorism can be difficult and has been described as a 'fine line'.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The *Online Etymology Dictionary* records the English words "activism" and "activist" as in use in the political sense from the year 1920 or 1915 respectively.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The history of the word *activism* traces back to earlier understandings of collective behavior and social action.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] As late as 1969 *activism was* defined as "the policy or practice of doing things with decision and energy", without regard to a political signification, whereas *social action was* defined as "organized action taken by a group to improve social conditions", without regard to normative status.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Following the surge of "new social movements" in the United States during the 1960s, activism came to be understood as a rational and legitimate democratic form of protest or appeal.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] In English history, the Peasants' Revolt erupted in response to the imposition of a poll tax, and has been paralleled by other rebellions and revolutions in Hungary, Russia, and more recently, for example, Hong Kong.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] In 1930 under the leadership of Mahatma Gandhi thousands of protesting Indians participated in the Salt March, as a protest against the oppressive taxes of their government, resulting in the imprisonment of 60,000 people and eventually independence of their nation.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activism has had major impacts on Western societies as well, particularly over the past century through social movements such as the Labour movement, the women's rights movement, and the civil rights movement.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activism has often been thought to address either human rights or environmental concerns, but libertarian and religious right activism are also important types.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] In the 21st century, the intersection between human rights and environmentalism has become increasingly important, leading to criticism of the mainstream environmentalist movement and the development of the environmental justice and climate justice movements.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Human rights activism seeks to protect basic rights such as those laid out in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights including such liberties as: right to life, citizenship, and property, freedom of movement; constitutional freedoms of thought, expression, religion, peaceful assembly; and others.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The foundations of the global human rights movement involve resistance to colonialism, imperialism, slavery, racism, segregation, patriarchy, and oppression of indigenous peoples.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Instead, it is between an emergent group (Activists) that fuses *both ideologies* and a less ideological category of 'somewhat conservative' Establishment Republicans." One example of this activism is the Tea Party movement.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Pew Research identified a "group of 'Staunch Conservatives' (11 percent of the electorate) who are strongly religious, across-the-board socially and economically conservative, and more politically active than other groups on the Right.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activists employ many different methods, or tactics, in pursuit of their goals.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The tactics chosen are significant because they can determine how activists are perceived and what they are capable of accomplishing.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] For example, nonviolent tactics generally tend to garner more public sympathy than violent ones. and are more than twice as effective in achieving stated goals.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Historically, most activism has focused on creating substantive changes in the policy or practice of a government or industry.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Some activists try to persuade people to change their behavior directly (see also direct action), rather than to persuade governments to change laws.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] For example, the cooperative movement seeks to build new institutions which conform to cooperative principles, and generally does not lobby or protest politically.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Other activists try to persuade people or government policy to remain the same, in an effort to counter change.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Greta Thunberg a Swedish climate activist is known for founding the Fridays for Future movement.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Charles Tilly developed the concept of a "repertoire of contention", which describes the full range of tactics available to activists at a given time and place.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] This repertoire consists of all of the tactics which have been proven to be successful by activists in the past, such as boycotts, petitions, marches, and sit-ins, and can be drawn upon by any new activists and social movements.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activists may also innovate new tactics of protest.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] These may be entirely novel, such as Douglas Schuler's idea of an "activist road trip", or may occur in response to police oppression or countermovement resistance.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] New tactics then spread to others through a social process known as diffusion, and if successful, may become new additions to the activist repertoire.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activism is not an activity always performed by those who profess activism as a profession.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The term "activist" may apply broadly to anyone who engages in activism, or narrowly limited to those who choose political or social activism as a vocation or characteristic practice.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Helena Alviar Garcia has combined activism with her work as a legal scholar, resulting in academia being seen as activism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Judges may employ judicial activism to promote their own conception of the social good.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The definition of judicial activism and whether a specific decisions is activist are controversial political issues.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The legal systems of different nations vary in the extent that judicial activism may be permitted.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activists can also be public watchdogs and whistle blowers by holding government agencies accountable to oversight and transparency.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Political activism may also include political campaigning, lobbying, voting, or petitioning.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Often political activists also publish their ideas themselves via newsletters, periodicals, presses, or digital media.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Political activism does not depend on a specific ideology or national history, as can be seen, for example, in the importance of conservative British women in the 1920s on issues of tariffs.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Political activism, although often identified with young adults, occurs across peoples entire life-courses.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The power of Internet activism came into a global lens with the Arab Spring protests starting in late 2010.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] People living in the Middle East and North African countries that were experiencing revolutions used social networking to communicate information about protests, including videos recorded on smart phones, which put the issues in front of an international audience.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] This was one of the first occasions in which social networking technology was used by citizen-activists to circumvent state-controlled media and communicate directly with the rest of the world.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] These types of practices of Internet activism were later picked up and used by other activists in subsequent mass mobilizations, such as the 15-M Movement in Spain in 2011, Occupy Gezi in Turkey in 2013, and more.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Online "left- and right-wing activists use digital and legacy media differently to achieve political goals".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Left-wing online activists are usually more involved in traditional "hashtag activism" and offline protest, while right-wing activists may "manipulate legacy media, migrate to alternative platforms, and work strategically with partisan media to spread their messages".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Research suggests right-wing online activists are more likely to use "strategic disinformation and conspiracy theories".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Internet activism may also refer to activism which focuses on protecting or changing the Internet itself, also known as digital rights.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The Digital Rights movement consists of activists and organizations, such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation, who work to protect the rights of people in relation to new technologies, particularly concerning the Internet and other information and communications technologies.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Many contemporary activists now utilize new tactics through the Internet and other information and communication technologies (ICTs), also known as Internet activism or cyber-activism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Some scholars argue that many of these new tactics are digitally analogous to the traditional offline tools of contention.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Other digital tactics may be entire new and unique, such as certain types of hacktivism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Together they form a new "digital repertoire of contention" alongside the existing offline one.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The rising use of digital tools and platforms by activists has also increasingly led to the creation of decentralized networks of activists that are self-organized and leaderless, or what is known as **franchise activism**.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Economic activism involves using the economic power of government, consumers, and businesses for social and economic policy change.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Both conservative and liberal groups use economic activism as a form of pressure to influence companies and organizations to oppose or support particular political, religious, or social values and behaviors.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] This may be done through ethical consumerism to reinforce "good" behavior and support companies one would like to succeed, or through boycott or divestment to penalize "bad" behavior and pressure companies to change or go out of business.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Brand activism is the type of activism in which business plays a leading role in the processes of social change.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Applying brand activism, businesses show concern for the communities they serve, and their economic, social, and environmental problems, which allows businesses to build sustainable and long-term relationships with the customers and prospects.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Kotler and Sarkar defined the phenomenon as an attempt by firms to solve the global problems its future customers and employees care about.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Consumer activism consists of activism carried out on behalf of consumers for consumer protection or by consumers themselves.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] For instance, activists in the free produce movement of the late 1700s protested against slavery by boycotting goods produced with slave labor.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Today, vegetarianism, veganism, and freeganism are all forms of consumer activism which boycott certain types of products.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Shareholder activism involves shareholders using an equity stake in a corporation to put pressure on its management.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The goals of activist shareholders range from financial (increase of shareholder value through changes in corporate policy, financing structure, cost cutting, etc.) to non-financial (disinvestment from particular countries, adoption of environmentally friendly policies, etc.).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Design activism locates design at the center of promoting social change, raising awareness on social/political issues, or questioning problems associated with mass production and consumerism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Design Activism is not limited to one type of design.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Art activism or artivism utilizes the medium of visual art as a method of social or political commentary.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Art activism can activate utopian thinking, which is imagining about an ideal society that is different from the current society, which is found to be effective for increasing collective action intentions.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Fashion activism was coined by Celine Semaan.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Fashion activism is a type of activism that ignites awareness by giving consumers tools to support change, specifically in the fashion industry.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] It has been used as an umbrella term for many social and political movements that have taken place in the industry.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Fashion Activism uses a participatory approach to a political activity.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Craft activism or craftivism is a type of visual activism that allows people to bring awareness to political or social discourse.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] It is a creative approach to activism as it allows people to send short and clear messages to society.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] People who contribute to craftivism are called "craftivists".
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Activism in literature may publish written works that express intended or advocated reforms.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Alternatively, literary activism may also seek to reform perceived corruption or entrenched systems of power within the publishing industry.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Science activism may include efforts to better communicate science or advocate for funding of scientific research.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] It may also include efforts to increase perceived legitimacy of particular scientific fields or respond to the politicization of particular fields.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Some forms of science or scholarly activism on political topics can reduce the separation of science from political advocacy and reduce the credibility of science.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The March for Science held around the world in 2017 and 2018 were notable examples of science activism.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Approaches to science activism vary from protests to more psychological, marketing-oriented approaches that takes into account such factors as individual sense of self, aversion to solutions to problems, and social perceptions.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Some groups and organizations participate in activism to such an extent that it can be considered as an industry.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] In these cases, activism is often done full-time, as part of an organization's core business.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Many organizations in the activism industry are either non-profit organizations or non-governmental organizations with specific aims and objectives in mind.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Most activist organizations do not manufacture goods, but rather mobilize personnel to recruit funds and gain media coverage.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] The term *activism industry* has often been used to refer to outsourced fundraising operations.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] However, activist organizations engage in other activities as well.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Lobbying, or the influencing of decisions made by government, is another activist tactic.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Many groups, including law firms, have designated staff assigned specifically for lobbying purposes.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] In the United States, lobbying is regulated by the federal government.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Many government systems encourage public support of non-profit organizations by granting various forms of tax relief for donations to charitable organizations.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/activist] Governments may attempt to deny these benefits to activists by restricting the political activity of tax-exempt organizations.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] The **Christian Vegetarian Association** (**CVA**) is an international, interdenominational Christian vegetarian organization that promotes responsible stewardship of God's creation through plant-based eating.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] The CVA claims to advocate vegetarianism from a biblically-based, Christian perspective and sees dietary choice as a valid way to bear witness to Christ's ministry of love, peace, mercy and compassion, and prepare for the Peaceable Kingdom as foretold in the Bible.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] The Christian Vegetarian Association (CVA) encourages Christians to reduce or eliminate animal products as part of their Christian calling to be good stewards of God's Creation.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] The CVA promotes the ethical, environmental and health benefits of plant-based diets.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] They assert that there is a connection between animal-based diets and world hunger, ecological damage, animal mistreatment and human disease.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] The CVA was founded in 1999 by Nathan Braun.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] Braun organized a board of professors, theologians, and activists.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] In 2000, the CVA produced its first edition of *What Would Jesus Eat...Today?* which has an annual distribution rate of approximately 250,000 and been translated into several languages.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] In 2002, CVA founder Nathan Braun and co-chairman Stephen R.
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] Kaufman, M.D. published the first edition of *Good News for All Creation: Vegetarianism as Christian Stewardship* (2002: Vegetarian Advocates Press) and a revised, second version two years later (2004: Vegetarian Advocates Press).
[src:christian-vegetarian-association/christian-vegetarian-association] In 2006, the CVA produced a short documentary film with an accompanying study guide called *Honoring God's Creation*.
